Date: 7/10/1933
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: <i>Creek</i>: Any stream, from a mountain torrent to a tidal stream, which is too small to call <i>river</i>. A much misused term. [1951, p.364 Many <i>creeks</i> are full-sized rivers, especially in flood.] (Butler A First Year in Canterbury Settlement], p.46; [1898 Morris Austral-English]) [This usage belongs originally to the U.[1873 Lady Barker Station Amusements]--A.W.]
Notes: Acland Glossary

Date: 13/1/1934
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 13
Edition:
Quote: <i>Creek.</i>-A much misused term. Many are full sized rivers; for instance, Pyke's Creek, N.W. Otago, which is generally unfordable on foot.
